# Multi-Module Gradle Governance

## Purpose

Use this rule for changes affecting:

- module creation, removal, rename, or merge
- project inclusion in `settings`
- inter-module dependency direction
- API/runtime classpath boundaries
- BOM and version ownership
- convention plugins
- root build responsibilities
- publication coordinates or metadata
- starter dependency graphs
- architecture fitness tasks

This rule governs **module architecture**.

For low-level Gradle DSL and task implementation details, also follow the main Gradle rule.

## Repository Facts First

Before changing the module graph, inspect:

- `settings.gradle` or `settings.gradle.kts`
- root build file
- affected module build files
- current project dependency graph
- public API and runtime consumers
- custom source sets
- publications
- architecture fitness tasks
- CI references
- current ADRs and module-taxonomy documentation

Do not infer module ownership from names alone.

Do not create a module or dependency edge solely because it makes compilation easier.

## Module Boundary Test

A module is justified only when it represents at least one real boundary:

- independently published contract
- distinct runtime or classloader
- optional dependency isolation
- servlet/reactive isolation
- agent/application separation
- independently reusable capability
- independently testable adapter
- meaningful reduction of consumer dependencies
- separately governed lifecycle or release artifact

Before adding a module, document:

```text
Owner:
Consumers:
Published or internal:
Runtime/classloader:
Public contracts:
Dependencies exposed:
Dependencies hidden:
Why a package is insufficient:
Tests:
Publication:
```

Do not create a module merely to move packages around or increase architectural ceremony.

## Current Platform Module Roles

### `platform-tracing-api`

Owns:

- application-facing tracing contracts
- intentional external SPIs
- immutable value and specification types
- classloader-neutral wire/control types
- public result and violation models

Must not depend on core, Spring, JMX/OpenMBean, or OTel SDK implementation.

### `platform-tracing-otel`

Owns:

- runtime implementation
- domain validation
- lifecycle and state
- sampling and scrubbing policy
- runtime-control handlers
- last-known-good state
- safety invariants

May depend on API.

Must not depend on Spring Boot auto-configuration, servlet, WebFlux, or deployment modules.

### Spring Boot auto-configuration

Owns:

- wiring
- typed properties
- conditions
- startup diagnostics
- Actuator integration

May depend on API/core.

Must not own runtime algorithms or domain validation.

### WebMVC and WebFlux adapters

Remain independent.

Neither adapter may depend on the other.

### OTel extension

Owns:

- Java agent and SDK integration
- sampler/processor/exporter glue
- JMX/OpenMBean adapters
- classloader-sensitive bridges

Must not become an alternate domain core.

### Starters

Remain thin dependency aggregators.

They must not contain runtime algorithms, domain policy, or duplicate auto-configuration.

### Test, sample, benchmark, and E2E modules

May depend on production modules.

Production modules must not depend on them.

## Allowed Dependency Direction

```text
platform-tracing-otel
    -> platform-tracing-api

platform-tracing-spring-boot-autoconfigure
    -> platform-tracing-api
    -> platform-tracing-otel

platform-tracing-autoconfigure-webmvc
    -> approved API/core/autoconfigure modules

platform-tracing-autoconfigure-webflux
    -> approved API/core/autoconfigure modules

platform-tracing-otel-javaagent-extension
    -> approved API/core modules
    -> OTel integration artifacts

starters
    -> matching auto-configuration/integration modules

tests, samples, benchmarks, and E2E
    -> production modules under test
```

## Forbidden Dependency Direction

Do not introduce:

- API -> core
- core -> Spring Boot auto-configuration
- WebMVC -> WebFlux
- WebFlux -> servlet
- production -> test/sample/benchmark/E2E
- API -> JMX/OpenMBean implementation
- API -> OTel SDK implementation without an approved public contract
- runtime module -> starter
- transport adapter -> ownership of domain policy
- project cycles

Do not solve a cycle by:

- changing `implementation` to `api`
- making helpers public
- introducing static holders
- duplicating contracts
- moving domain logic into auto-configuration
- adding a bridge module without a real boundary

Fix ownership.

## Root Project Governance

The root project may own:

- project inclusion
- plugin and repository management
- common group/version metadata
- aggregate verification
- architecture fitness registration
- narrow shared conventions when no convention plugin exists

The root project must not own:

- production runtime logic
- business/domain dependencies
- application-specific configuration
- module-specific dependency graphs
- environment-specific behavior
- network or Docker access during configuration

Do not turn the root build into a giant imperative coordinator.

Do not rewrite existing root logic as a side effect of an unrelated module change.

## Settings Governance

`settings.gradle` or `settings.gradle.kts` owns:

- project inclusion
- plugin management
- dependency repository management where configured
- version catalogs
- included builds
- feature previews

Feature modules must not redefine repositories unless explicitly approved.

When renaming or removing a project:

1. update settings
2. update all project dependencies
3. update task and CI references
4. update publications
5. update docs and samples
6. remove old project path
7. scan for old coordinates
8. run full verification

Do not keep an empty compatibility project by default.

## Version Governance

Use the repository's current version-management mechanism.

Allowed owners may include:

- Spring Boot dependency management
- platform BOM
- version catalog
- approved root or convention logic

Do not require a version catalog if the repository does not use one.

Forbidden:

- dynamic versions
- `latest.release`
- duplicate version declarations
- module-local overrides without documented reason
- conflicting BOM ownership

When overriding a centrally managed version, document:

```text
Artifact:
Existing owner:
Override reason:
Security/compatibility evidence:
Affected modules:
Removal criteria:
```

## BOM Governance

BOM modules own dependency alignment, not runtime logic.

A BOM must not:

- contain implementation code
- add runtime behavior
- depend on starters
- hide incompatible dependency families
- expose test-only artifacts

Verify generated dependency constraints and publication metadata.

Do not use `enforcedPlatform` casually in published libraries; it can constrain consumers beyond the intended contract.

## Convention Plugin Governance

A convention plugin should configure one coherent concern.

It must:

- be idempotent
- use lazy configuration where practical
- avoid unrelated plugin application
- avoid hidden dependency injection
- avoid network or filesystem mutation during `apply`
- avoid eager task realization
- keep module-specific logic out of generic conventions

Do not introduce `afterEvaluate` for ordinary configuration.

Do not create a convention plugin for one trivial line or one module-only setting.

Do not migrate existing build logic into convention plugins inside an unrelated feature change.

## Dependency Scope Governance

Dependency scope is architecture.

Use:

- `api` only for intentionally exposed compile contracts
- `implementation` for internal implementation
- `compileOnly` only for a genuine provided-runtime contract
- `runtimeOnly` for runtime-only dependencies
- test scopes only for tests and fixtures

For `compileOnly`, document who provides the dependency at runtime.

Do not describe a module as runtime-independent if its executable main code references a compile-only type that consumers must provide.

Inspect compile and runtime classpaths after scope changes.

## Starter Governance

Starters must:

- aggregate only intended modules
- preserve servlet/reactive separation
- avoid optional integration leakage
- expose correct runtime dependencies
- avoid version ownership
- remain free of runtime code

Verify:

- servlet starter does not pull WebFlux
- reactive starter does not pull servlet stack
- optional integrations remain optional
- generated POM/module metadata is correct
- starter dependency smoke remains green

## Publication Governance

For each published module, verify:

- coordinates
- artifact contents
- generated POM
- Gradle module metadata
- API versus runtime scopes
- sources JAR
- Javadoc JAR where applicable
- absence of test/internal classes
- absence of obsolete ServiceLoader descriptors

A successful local compile does not prove a correct consumer contract.

Because the platform is pre-production, incorrect coordinates or publications may be removed or renamed directly when justified.

Do not keep forwarding artifacts or duplicate old/new coordinates by default.

## Generated Metadata and Source Sets

Custom source sets and generated artifacts are part of the module contract.

Inspect:

- agent smoke applications
- JMX/classloader fixtures
- ServiceLoader provider JARs
- E2E fixtures
- benchmarks
- generated descriptors
- baseline files

When APIs or module paths change, migrate these consumers too.

Do not leave stale descriptors or generated baselines in unrelated working-tree changes.

## Architecture Fitness

Protect at least:

- API does not depend on core
- core does not depend on Spring
- WebMVC and WebFlux remain isolated
- starters remain thin
- production modules do not depend on test modules
- JMX/OpenMBean does not leak into API
- OTel SDK implementation does not leak into API
- forbidden project cycles fail the build
- obsolete project paths and coordinates do not return
- dependency scope regressions are detected where practical

Do not weaken architecture gates to make generated code compile.

## Pre-Production Policy

Breaking module, coordinate, dependency, and publication changes are allowed when they materially improve:

- ownership
- dependency direction
- classloader isolation
- public API purity
- consumer classpaths
- publication correctness
- verification quality

Prefer direct repository-wide migration and deletion over:

- compatibility projects
- forwarding artifacts
- deprecated module aliases
- duplicate publications
- dual dependency paths

Do not use pre-production status to justify arbitrary module churn.

## Verification

For module-graph changes:

1. compile affected production source sets
2. compile affected test and custom source sets
3. run focused tests
4. inspect compile/runtime dependency reports
5. run module taxonomy and architecture fitness
6. verify Javadoc/publication when contracts changed
7. run full build
8. run E2E when runtime/classloader/integration boundaries changed

Useful commands:

```powershell
.\gradlew.bat :<module>:dependencies --configuration compileClasspath --no-daemon
.\gradlew.bat :<module>:dependencies --configuration runtimeClasspath --no-daemon
.\gradlew.bat pr1ModuleTaxonomyVerify pr4ArchitectureFitnessVerify --no-daemon
.\gradlew.bat build --warning-mode all --no-daemon
```

Verify a named task exists before relying on it.

## Required Report

A multi-module governance report must include:

```text
Decision:
Modules added/removed/renamed:
Old ownership:
Target ownership:
Dependency edges added/removed:
Public API impact:
Compile/runtime classpath impact:
Version/BOM impact:
Publication impact:
Custom source sets and generated metadata:
Architecture gates:
Tests and E2E:
Migration:
Residual risks:
```

Use `PASS`, `PASS_WITH_WARNINGS`, `INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE`, or `FAIL` according to executed evidence.
